  "chapter": {
    "number": 4,
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "content": [
          "The Evil of Oppression"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 1,
        "content": [
          "Again I looked, and I considered all the oppression taking place under the sun. I saw the tears of the oppressed, and they had no comforter; the power lay in the hands of their oppressors, and there was no comforter."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 2,
        "content": [
          "So I admired the dead, who had already died, above the living, who are still alive."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 3,
        "content": [
          "But better than both is he who has not yet existed, who has not seen the evil that is done under the sun."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 4,
        "content": [
          "I saw that all labor and success spring from a man’s envy of his neighbor. This too is futile and a pursuit of the wind."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 5,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The fool folds his hands",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and consumes his own flesh.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 6,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Better one handful with tranquility",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "than two handfuls with toil and pursuit of the wind.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 7,
        "content": [
          "Again, I saw futility under the sun."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 8,
        "content": [
          "There is a man all alone, without even a son or brother. And though there is no end to his labor, his eyes are still not content with his wealth: “For whom do I toil and bereave my soul of enjoyment?” This too is futile—a miserable task."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 9,
        "content": [
          "Two are better than one, because they have a good return for their labor."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 10,
        "content": [
          "For if one falls down, his companion can lift him up; but pity the one who falls without another to help him up!"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 11,
        "content": [
          "Again, if two lie down together, they will keep warm; but how can one keep warm alone?"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 12,
        "content": [
          "And though one may be overpowered, two can resist. Moreover, a cord of three strands is not quickly broken."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "content": [
          "The Futility of Power"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 13,
        "content": [
          "Better is a poor but wise youth than an old but foolish king who no longer knows how to take a warning."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 14,
        "content": [
          "For the youth has come from the prison to the kingship, though he was born poor in his own kingdom."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 15,
        "content": [
          "I saw that all who lived and walked under the sun followed this second one, the youth who succeeded the king."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 16,
        "content": [
          "There is no limit to all the people who were before them. Yet the successor will not be celebrated by those who come even later. This too is futile and a pursuit of the wind."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "footnotes": []
